    <subfield code="s">66859</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1343315/files/diagram.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00000 \small A sphere $\mathscr{S}$ on the event horizon bounds a spacelike hypersurface, a large portion of which coincides with an $r =$ constant hypersurface. We show this hypersurface with one dimension suppressed, and cut in the middle, omitting the long cylindrical part which gives the main contribution to its volume. We also illustrate the argument showing that most of the volume is contained in a region out of causal contact with matter that has advanced far into the black hole.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="s">783402</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1343315/files/volym.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00001 \small The volume of a hypersurface of constant $r$ in the Kerr geometry is given by Vol $= 2\pi m^2 v f(\frac{r}{m},\frac{a}{m})$ (eq. \eqref{eq:vol}). The figure shows how the numerical factor $f$ depends on our choice of $r$, for values of $a/m$ ranging from 0.1 to 0.9 in even steps, and for $a/m = 0.99$ on the innermost curve.</subfield>
  </datafield>
